Ok, nice. I like that option. The only question I have about this is that if property could be changed from UI by users after inserted in "cluster_details", as I have observed most properties set in "cluster_details" table are not listed in the UI (Infrastructure -> Clusters -> Cluster X -> Settings).
How can I do to enable changing it from the UI instead of updating DB table?

@nvazquez just a quick update.
I was going over "org.apache.cloudstack.api.command.admin.config.ListCfgsByCmd.execute()" that is used to list the cluster configuration at the UI. It seems that it uses the configuration table too. The method used is 
"com.cloud.server.ManagementService.searchForConfigurations(ListCfgsByCmd)". I did not have much time to analyse it, but I believe that a careful inspection can help us to understand the way those configurations work.

@serg38 and I found out a way to change this property from UI, inserting the property in "configuration" table with scope="Cluster", insert sql:

INSERT INTO `cloud`.`configuration` 
(`category`, `instance`, `component`, `name`, `description`, `default_value`, `updated`, `scope`, `is_dynamic`) VALUES 
('Advanced', 'DEFAULT', â€˜CapacityManager', 'cluster.storage.operations.exclude', 'Exclude cluster from storage operations', 'false', now(), 'Cluster', '1');

This way, all clusters will be inheriting the property in its default value, which is false. So if you want to set it true, you can do it from UI, and will be inserted in "cluster_details" table with value = true.

